#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:3
#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:15
msgid "How Tradeoffs is written"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:8
msgid ""
"How Tradeoffs is written — the editorial principles behind a five-minute "
"civic game that simulates pressure, not ideology."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:17
msgid "The game holds up a mirror; it never grades the reflection."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:20
msgid ""
"Every scenario is designed to make you feel a real trade-off, not to teach "
"you what to think. Here is the editorial discipline that keeps it honest."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:27
msgid "What Tradeoffs is"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:29
msgid ""
"Tradeoffs is a five-turn game about governing. You face one crisis with no "
"good answers. Borrow now and pay later, or cut now and lose trust. Build "
"fast and fracture the country, or move slowly while the queues grow."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:32
msgid ""
"Each turn presents three choices. Every choice helps at least one part of "
"society and hurts another. Some come due immediately. Some come due later, "
"the way real policy does. After five turns, you see what kind of leader you "
"became under pressure — and what kind of society you left behind."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:37
msgid "What Tradeoffs is not"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:39
msgid ""
"It is not a policy simulator. Real economies have hundreds of levers; we "
"abstract to the dozen that show up in the news."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:40
msgid ""
"It is not a quiz with right answers. The headlines you collect describe what"
" happened — they do not grade the choice."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:41
msgid ""
"It is not a partisan litmus test. Every choice is written so a thoughtful "
"person could defend it from inside a real political tradition."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:42
msgid ""
"It is not an opinion piece. We use real research, but every scenario is "
"fiction, set in no country you can name."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:49
msgid "Ten principles"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:53
msgid "We simulate pressure, not ideology."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:54
msgid ""
"The game is about the feeling of tradeoffs — relief and regret, urgency and "
"unintended consequence. It is not about whether you should be a centrist or "
"a leftist or a libertarian. The same scenario is written so any of those "
"starting points can navigate it without feeling cornered."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:57
msgid "Multiple paths remain viable."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:58
msgid ""
"If one choice in a turn is strictly better than the others — no real-world "
"cost, no plausible downside — that turn is broken and we rewrite it. The "
"interesting tension lives in choices that are all defensible from somewhere."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:61
msgid "Consequences describe, never judge."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:62
msgid ""
"We say \"Retirees protest. Bond yields fall — slightly.\" We do not say "
"\"The cruel pension cut sparked outrage.\" The verbs are observational. The "
"verdict belongs to the player."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:65
msgid "Systems, not tribes."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:66
msgid ""
"No choice is tagged with a party label, a personality, or a country. The "
"pressures are universal — debt, housing, energy, migration — and the actors "
"are descriptive: unions, investors, retirees, regulators. If a reaction "
"would only make sense inside one political tradition, we cut it."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:69
msgid "Framing is audited for balance."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:70
msgid ""
"Every scenario goes through a checklist: are the choices labelled neutrally?"
" Do the reactions name real stakeholders without mocking them? Does any "
"single choice feel written to be wrong? When the answer is yes to that last "
"one, the scenario fails the validator and goes back for rewrite."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:73
msgid "Causality is simplified, not claimed as truth."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:74
msgid ""
"A choice that lowers public spending will lower debt pressure in the game. "
"In the real world it depends on a hundred variables. We make the mechanic "
"legible so the lesson lands: every lever has weight."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:77
msgid "Global first."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:78
msgid ""
"Scenarios are written so they read clearly in São Paulo, Lagos, Mumbai, "
"Berlin, and Iowa. If a scenario needs a footnote about a country-specific "
"institution to make sense, we rewrite the scenario."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:81
msgid "Players discover contradictions; we never accuse."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:82
msgid ""
"If you start by protecting fairness and end by cutting benefits twice, the "
"game will gently note that — not as a moral failing, but as an observation. "
"\"Under pressure\" is the word for it. Politicians do this. Ordinary people "
"do this. The mirror is the point."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:85
msgid "We show tradeoffs, not purity."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:86
msgid ""
"There is no path through any scenario that improves every stat. The best "
"runs are the most interesting — the ones where you can articulate what you "
"protected and what you sacrificed."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:89
msgid "When in doubt, cut the lecture."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:90
msgid ""
"The five turns are short on purpose. If a line of prose is teaching rather "
"than evoking, it goes. If a consequence headline reads like a press release,"
" it goes. The game is a feeling, not a class."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:98
msgid "What the validator catches"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:99
msgid ""
"Every scenario passes through a publish gate before it can appear in the "
"rotation. The gate enforces — automatically, in the codebase, with tests — "
"the rules that the prose alone cannot guarantee:"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:101
msgid ""
"Five turns, in the order hook → confidence → crack → oh no → legacy. The "
"emotional shape is fixed; the content varies."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:102
msgid ""
"Three choices per turn, every choice must help at least one stat that the "
"player can see."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:103
msgid ""
"At least one delayed consequence per scenario, because the \"oh no\" beat "
"only lands when an early choice comes due later."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:104
msgid ""
"Three memory callbacks on turn four — the run is only yours if turn four "
"references your earlier moves by name."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:105
msgid ""
"No choice can sit on both sides of an opposing axis (welfare and austerity, "
"centralise and decentralise) — that would confuse the engine that tracks "
"your value shifts across the run."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:106
msgid ""
"No turn where every choice shows only down-arrows to the player. If a turn "
"reads as picked-on, the scenario fails."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:109
msgid ""
"These rules are not aspirations. They are the conditions under which a "
"scenario can be published. The corpus you play has all passed them."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:114
msgid "Who writes the scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:116
msgid ""
"Tradeoffs is written by a small team using AI as a drafting partner. The "
"founder makes every balance decision, sets every tag, audits every "
"consequence headline, and signs off on every publish. AI helps with the "
"first pass — the policy lever search, the dramatic shape, the phrasing — and"
" is never trusted to make the choice about whether a scenario is fair."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:119
msgid ""
"Every scenario gets a self-sensitivity audit against the principles above "
"before it ships. Where the topic is delicate — migration, populism, "
"surveillance, corruption — we look for outside reads from people whose lives"
" the topic actually touches."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:124
msgid "When we get it wrong"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:126
msgid ""
"We will. Five turns and three choices is a tight budget for handling complex"
" topics, and a writer with a perspective will leak through, no matter how "
"hard we audit."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:129
msgid ""
"If you finish a scenario and feel cornered into one ideology — if any single"
" choice reads to you as a straw man written by the other side — tell us. The"
" fix is usually a rewrite, not an argument. Reach us at"
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:130
msgid " with the scenario name and the choice that landed wrong."
msgstr ""

#: app/templates/game/editorial_principles.html:137
msgid "Every choice costs something."
msgstr ""

